[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":338},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F":314,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F":323},"\u002Fvue\u002F20200522\u002F1986801509\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":295,"date":296,"description":297,"extension":298,"lang":299,"meta":300,"navigation":301,"path":302,"readingMinutes":303,"seo":304,"standalone":305,"stem":306,"tags":307,"tldr":311,"updated":296,"url":312,"__hash__":313},"content\u002Fen\u002FVue\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli.md","How to Add ESLint to Vue CLI","9051086891",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":288},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,44,47,56,59,66,69,75,79,90,100,140,147,161,189,202,207,211,216,232,242,249,266,270,284],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"For real-world projects we usually add a code style manager (ESLint) to keep code quality consistent — but how do you actually add it correctly to a Vue CLI project?",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"the-vue-cli-way","The Vue CLI way",[17,25,26],{},"The official docs cover this — just run this inside your Vue CLI project:",[28,29,34],"pre",{"className":30,"code":31,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-cmd shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","vue add eslint\n","cmd","",[35,36,37],"code",{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,39,42],"span",{"class":40,"line":41},"line",1,[38,43,31],{},[17,45,46],{},"Or alternatively:",[28,48,50],{"className":30,"code":49,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"vue add @vue\u002Fcli-plugin-eslint\n",[35,51,52],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,53,54],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,55,49],{},[17,57,58],{},"I use Airbnb style when writing code (if you're not super comfortable with JavaScript yet, I'd recommend Standard — less frustrating).",[17,60,61],{},[62,63],"img",{"alt":64,"src":65},"Pick an ESLint config","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FVue\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-22%2023.59.02.png",[17,67,68],{},"For \"Pick additional lint features\" I usually pick both, but the first one is fine.",[17,70,71],{},[62,72],{"alt":73,"src":74},"Pick additional lint features","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FVue\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-23%2000.01.04.png",[12,76,78],{"id":77},"differences-from-plain-eslint-init","Differences from plain ESLint init",[17,80,81,82,85,86,89],{},"Let's look at the difference between ",[35,83,84],{},"vue add eslint"," and the more common ",[35,87,88],{},"eslint --init",".",[17,91,92,93,95,96,99],{},"When you use ",[35,94,84],{},", the ESLint config's ",[35,97,98],{},"extends"," looks like:",[28,101,105],{"className":102,"code":103,"language":104,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","extends: [\n  'plugin:vue\u002Fessential',\n  '@vue\u002Fairbnb',\n],\n","js",[35,106,107,116,126,134],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,108,109,112],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,110,98],{"class":111},"s_sBn",[38,113,115],{"class":114},"sMAXC",": [\n",[38,117,119,123],{"class":40,"line":118},2,[38,120,122],{"class":121},"sTRMh","  'plugin:vue\u002Fessential'",[38,124,125],{"class":114},",\n",[38,127,129,132],{"class":40,"line":128},3,[38,130,131],{"class":121},"  '@vue\u002Fairbnb'",[38,133,125],{"class":114},[38,135,137],{"class":40,"line":136},4,[38,138,139],{"class":114},"],\n",[17,141,142,143,146],{},"We'll come back to ",[35,144,145],{},"plugin:vue\u002Fessential"," in a moment. Let's look at the second line first.",[17,148,149,150,153,154,157,158,160],{},"Notice ",[35,151,152],{},"airbnb"," has ",[35,155,156],{},"@vue"," in front. That's the Vue-customised version of the Airbnb rules. If you'd used ",[35,159,88],{}," instead, you'd typically get:",[28,162,164],{"className":102,"code":163,"language":104,"meta":33,"style":33},"extends: [\n  'plugin:vue\u002Fessential',\n  'airbnb-base',\n],\n",[35,165,166,172,178,185],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,167,168,170],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,169,98],{"class":111},[38,171,115],{"class":114},[38,173,174,176],{"class":40,"line":118},[38,175,122],{"class":121},[38,177,125],{"class":114},[38,179,180,183],{"class":40,"line":128},[38,181,182],{"class":121},"  'airbnb-base'",[38,184,125],{"class":114},[38,186,187],{"class":40,"line":136},[38,188,139],{"class":114},[17,190,191,192,194,195,198,199,201],{},"The second line differs. What's the difference? The rules. If you use ",[35,193,88],{}," to add ESLint, you'll find errors you can never seem to fully fix — most notably ",[35,196,197],{},"Unable to resolve path to module",". That's because ",[35,200,88],{}," doesn't customise rules for Vue CLI, so the rules don't quite match the project conventions.",[17,203,204,205,89],{},"So for Vue CLI specifically, definitely use ",[35,206,84],{},[12,208,210],{"id":209},"the-plugin-essential-rule","The plugin essential rule",[17,212,213,215],{},[35,214,145],{}," is Vue's official style rule set. There are four tiers:",[217,218,219,223,226,229],"ul",{},[220,221,222],"li",{},"base — basic rules",[220,224,225],{},"essential — default rules",[220,227,228],{},"strongly-recommended — recommended rules",[220,230,231],{},"recommended — strictest rules",[17,233,234,235,238,239,89],{},"To change tier, just edit the part after ",[35,236,237],{},"vue\u002F"," — e.g. ",[35,240,241],{},"plugin:vue\u002Fstrongly-recommended",[17,243,244,245,248],{},"I'd recommend sticking with the default ",[35,246,247],{},"essential"," tier. It's already enough for solid code quality, so I wouldn't change it.",[17,250,251,252,259,260,265],{},"For the full rule set, see the ",[253,254,258],"a",{"href":255,"rel":256},"https:\u002F\u002Feslint.vuejs.org\u002Frules\u002F",[257],"nofollow","official docs"," and the ",[253,261,264],{"href":262,"rel":263},"https:\u002F\u002Fvuejs.org\u002Fstyle-guide\u002F",[257],"Style Guide"," — both have good examples.",[12,267,269],{"id":268},"references","References",[217,271,272,278],{},[220,273,274],{},[253,275,277],{"href":255,"rel":276},[257],"eslint-plugin-vue",[220,279,280],{},[253,281,283],{"href":262,"rel":282},[257],"Vue Style Guide",[285,286,287],"style",{},"html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}",{"title":33,"searchDepth":118,"depth":118,"links":289},[290,291,292,293,294],{"id":14,"depth":118,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":118,"text":23},{"id":77,"depth":118,"text":78},{"id":209,"depth":118,"text":210},{"id":268,"depth":118,"text":269},"Vue","2020-05-22 23:48:14","Most projects add a code style manager (ESLint) to keep code quality consistent — but how should you actually add it to a Vue CLI project?","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli","2",{"title":6,"description":297},false,"en\u002FVue\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli",[308,295,309,310],"JavaScript","Vue Cli","ESLint",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F22\u002Fadd-eslint-to-vue-cli\u002F","mb9Ea1dYl4SA54UN7NC8jorjRIozx6B7kmDG968EeXg",{"newer":315,"older":319},{"url":316,"title":317,"date":318},"\u002Fen\u002Fcss\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F23\u002Fcss-design-patterns-sass-7